Research Paper 
Gut-brain-crosstalk- the vagus nerve and the microbiota-gut-brain axis in 
depression. A narrative review 
Sabrina M¨orkl a,*, Mary I Butler b, Jolana Wagner-Skacel a 
a Division of Medical Psychology, Psychosomatics and Psychotherapeutic Medicine, Medical University of Graz, Austria 
b Department of Psychiatry, Cork University Hospital, Cork, Ireland   
A R T I C L E  I N F O   
Keywords: 
Vagus nerve 
Microbiota gut brain axis 
Depression 
Inflammation 
Anti-inflammatory reflex 
A B S T R A C T   
This narrative review summarizes key aspects of vagus nerve function as a main player in the microbiota-gut- 
brain axis in depression. Gut microbes as well as their metabolites signal directly to the vagus nerve via 
specialized enteroendocrine cells called “neuropods”. Some gut microbes, such as Lactobacillus rhamnosus, do not 
exhibit anti-anxiety effects in animal models when the vagus nerve is cut. Furthermore, vagus nerve function 
correlates with gut microbiota diversity, and short-chain fatty acid producers, such as Lactobacillales and 
Ruminococcaceae, are more abundant in individuals with better vagus function. The vagus nerve is activated by 
several neurotransmitters produced by the gut microbiota and regulates a cholinergic anti-inflammatory 
pathway (CAIP), which attenuates inflammation and decreases intestinal permeability, which may be relevant 
in the inflammatory subtype of depression. Psychobiotics, pre-, pro and synbiotics, with effects on behavior, 
work via the vagus nerve, and could be used to enhance its function. More research on gut microbiome in­
teractions with the vagus nerve is necessary to develop targeted psychobiotics to improve vagus nerve function 
for optimal mental health.   
1. Introduction 
Psychiatry and microbiology have a shared history. In ancient times, 
fermented foods were used not only to cure bowel disorders, but also to 
treat accompanying anxiety or stress (Ni, 1995). An example of a pop­
ular fermented food is “douchi”, a fermented soybean, which is still 
valued today for its antioxidant properties (Wang et al., 2008). In China 
in the 4th century, “jinzhi”, “golden soup” or “yellow dragon soup”, a 
fecal suspension that can be considered the first orally administered 
fecal transplant, was documented in the Chinese materia medica (Wang 
et al., 2008). Later on, in the early 20th century, when psychiatry was 
dominated by the infectious theory of diseases, psychiatrists tried to 
alleviate mental disorders by reducing “autointoxication” caused by 
harmful bacteria and the removal of focal infection. At that time, it was 
believed that infections were causing a wide range of psychiatric dis­
orders by producing toxins that affected brain function. For example, 
psychiatrist Henry Cotton was using surgical procedures, including the 
removal of teeth, tonsils and parts of the gut to remove harmful bacteria 
from patients with mental disorders (Cotton, 2016; Davidson, 2016). 
Needless to say, these endeavours left the patients severely harmed and 
surgical procedures were responsible for a high death rate. At the same 
time, other psychiatrists were advocating for the use of beneficial mi­
crobes in fermented milk drinks to alleviate symptoms of depression. 
Interestingly, Philipps was publishing his results on Lactic acid bacillus 
for the treatment of depression in 1910 (Phillips, 1910). Another 
researcher, Julianelle, was arguing against Cotton in his manuscript on 
“implantation of bacillus acidophilus in persons with psychoses” stating 
that “we do not believe that colectomy, as advocated by Cotton, is 
correct. Putrefaction, if present, may be eliminated by a change in the 
intestinal flora” (Julianelle and Ebaugh, 1923). In the 1950′s, an anti­
biotic used in the treatment of tuberculosis was found to have antide­
pressant properties (Caldara and Marmiroli, 2021). Nearly one century 
later, bacterial treatments in for psychiatric patients have once again 
become popular with the emergence of 16S sequencing methods to 
investigate the gut microbiome (Butler et al., 2019; M¨orkl et al., 2020). 
2. The microbiota gut-brain axis and the vagus nerve 
The microbiota gut-brain axis acts as a bidirectional communication 
system between the gut and the brain and consists of endocrine, 
