Received 7 May 2023; Accepted 4 June 2023   
Journal of Affective Disorders Reports 13 (2023) 100607
2
immunological and neurological pathways (Liu and Zhu, 2018; M¨orkl 
et al., 2020). Its main neurological pathway is the vagus nerve, a mixed 
nerve consisting of 80% afferent and 20% efferent fibers (Bonaz et al., 
2018). Vagus afferents are polymodal and therefore respond to me­
chanical, chemical, or hormonal signals (Berthoud et al., 2004; Egerod 
et al., 2018). They can sense gut bacteria and their metabolites and 
transfer this information to the central nervous system. This sensing of 
gut bacteria and their metabolites is possible through special gut sensory 
epithelial cells first described in 2015, the so-called “neuro­
pods”(Bohorquez et al., 2015). Neuropod cells provide the foundation 
for the gut to transduce sensory signals from the intestinal milieu to the 
brain through fast neurotransmission onto neurons of the vagus nerve 
(Kaelberer et al., 2020). The activity of the vagus nerve is proportionally 
associated with health, well-being, relaxation, and even emotions like 
empathy, whereas decreased cardiac vagus activity relates to risk fac­
tors, such as morbidity, mortality, and stress (Thayer and Sternberg, 
2010). A well-functioning vagus nerve is also a causal element in facial 
emotion recognition, a theory that was first proposed by Darwin and 
recently affirmed by studies showing improved emotional recognition 
after peripheral vagus nerve stimulation (Colzato et al., 2017; Sellaro 
et al., 2018). 
3. The link between the vagus nerve and neuroinflammation 
Gut microbiome alterations are common in many neuropsychiatric 
disorders, such as anxiety disorders (Butler et al., 2023), depression, 
schizophrenia (Nikolova et al., 2021), anorexia nervosa (M¨orkl et al., 
2017), Alzheimer’s disease (Mar´c et al., 2022) and migraine (Kopchak 
et al., 2022). Interestingly, many of these diseases have common roots 
with regard to metabolic disturbances, oxidative stress, immune 
dysfunction, mitochondrial dysfunction and inflammation. When gut 
microbiota and metabolites are altered due to dysbiosis, this, together 
with stress, infection, antibiotics, or a poor diet can result in increased 
permeability of the intestinal barrier. Due to this “leaky gut”, antigens 
can enter the bloodstream causing an inflammatory response, and a rise 
in pro-inflammatory cytokines (Kelly et al., 2015). Inflammation can 
activate further pathways crucial for the emergence and chronicity of 
psychiatric disorders, such as alterations in the HPA axis or the synthesis 
of neurotransmitters. For example, in inflammatory conditions, meta­
bolism of the amino acid tryptophan is shunted towards the neurotoxic 
branch of the kynurenine pathway, quinolinic acid, thereby perpetu­
ating neuroinflammation, and reducing the availability of tryptophan 
for serotonin production (Kelly et al., 2016; Myint and Halaris, 2022). 
Notably, significantly elevated peripheral levels of C-reactive protein 
(CRP) are commonly reported as a non-specific diagnostic inflammatory 
marker in patients with depression (Edberg et al., 2018; Halaris et al., 
2022). 
Interestingly, the vagus nerve also regulates the CAIP, which atten­
uates inflammation and decreases intestinal permeability (Bonaz et al., 
2018). Therefore, a well-functioning vagus nerve prevents long-lasting 
inflammatory states. Acetylcholine, the major neurotransmitter of the 
vagus nerve, is essential for the inhibition of production of inflammatory 
cytokines. Macrophages and other cytokine-producing cells have 
acetylcholine receptors, which, when activated, decrease cytokine syn­
thesis (Tracey, 2007). 
4. Heart rate variability to measure vagus nerve function 
Besides being a risk marker of sudden cardiac death, vagus nerve 
function is altered in depression (Bassett and Psychiatry, 2016; Sgoifo 
et al., 2015) and can be assessed by measuring heart rate variability 
(HRV). HRV reflects cardiac autonomic regulation and refers to the 
degree of fluctuation in the length of the inter-beat (R-R) intervals ob­
tained from an electrocardiogram (ECG). These intervals are not con­
stant, but differ from beat to beat: essentially, a higher HRV (higher 
vagus activity) indicates better general health (Jarczok et al., 2015). 
Low vagus function is associated with decreases in HRV, leading to a 
more monotonous regularity and less heart rate fluctuation (Leistedt 
et al., 2011). For example, a meta-analysis based on data from 673 
depressed participants and 407 healthy controls revealed that patients 
with major depressive disorder showed significantly reduced HRV 
compared to controls. The severity of depression was negatively corre­
lated with HRV (r = −0.354, p <0 0.001) (Kemp et al., 2010; Koch et al., 
2019). Further, results of a meta-analysis generally showed negative 
associations between indices of HRV and markers of inflammation, and 
it was proposed that indices of HRV can be used to gage the activity of 
the neurophysiological pathway responsible for adaptively regulating 
inflammatory processes in humans (Williams et al., 2019), and, it may 
also predict treatment outcome in major depression (Hage et al., 2017). 
5. Gut microbiome and heart rate variability 
Currently, there is a paucity of human studies connecting the gut 
microbiome and HRV. One study, involving Belgian children, investi­
gated both the gut microbiota and short-term HRV (i.e., a five-minute 
measurement) (Michels et al., 2017) and found that a vagus HRV 
marker (low pnn50) was associated with lower alpha diversity, and gut 
microbial composition differed between children with high and low 
parasympathetic activity (Michels et al., 2019). In 2022, our group 
showed that 24-hour cardiac vagus activity was positively correlated 
with gut microbiota diversity and inversely with inflammatory param­
eters, such as IL-6 and CRP, in a pilot study with 73 female participants. 
We identified specific microbial communities that were more abundant 
in participants with higher vagus function, such as Clostridia, Lachno­
spira, Ruminococaceae, Faecalibacterium, Lactobacillales, and Strepto­
coccaceae, and identified two gut microbial enterotypes which differed 
significantly in terms of vagus function, gut microbiota diversity, age, 
BMI, CRP, and IL-6 (M¨orkl et al., 2022). In the same year, the Iwaki 
Health Promotion Project which included 950 community-dwelling 
participants found that higher gut microbial diversity and L. incertae 
sedis abundance were associated with higher HRV parameters in a 
90-second HRV measurement (Tsubokawa et al., 2022). Although vagus 
activity can be retrieved from short-term recordings, long-term HRV 
measurements provide additional information, as vagus activity exhibits 
circadian fluctuations, thus providing a more comprehensive marker of 
autonomic functioning (Laborde et al., 2017). 
6. Probiotics and the vagus nerve 
Interestingly, changes in the intestinal flora following probiotic 
intake have been shown to significantly improve depressive symptoms, 
and are recommended in the World Federation of Societies for Biological 
Psychiatry (WFSBP) guidelines as add-on therapy (Sarris et al., 2022). 
Although the probiotic strains and combinations differ considerably 
between studies, the results of meta-analyses indicate that probiotic 
interventions significantly improve mood in patients suffering from 
clinical depression (Chao et al., 2020). Also, probiotics appear to affect 
HRV: A placebo-controlled trial by Da Silva, included 40 women with 
hypertension receiving either a multistrain probiotic containing Lacto­
bacillus paracasei LPC-37, Lactobacillus rhamnosus HN001, Lactobacillus 
acidophilus NCFM, and Bifidobacterium lactis HN019 or a placebo. Pro­
biotic administration reduced the low frequency (LF) oscillation and 
LF/high frequency (HF) ratio (p < 0.05) in the frequency domain of 
HRV, suggesting an improvement in autonomic modulation (da Silva 
et al., 2020). However, to date, there are no studies in patients with 
clinically diagnosed psychiatric disorders investigating the effects of 
probiotics on vagus nerve function, although there is promising research 
in animal studies. 
Gut bacteria can produce and regulate gastrointestinal levels of 
neurotransmitters, such as gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), seroto­
nin, norepinephrine, dopamine, histamine and acetylcholine. For 
example, Lactobacillus sp. can produce acetylcholine, the formerly called 
