Journal of Affective Disorders Reports 13 (2023) 100607
3
“Vagusstoff” (Oleskin and Shenderov, 2016). This is of particular 
importance as acetylcholine, GABA, serotonin and dopamine receptors 
have been found on vagus afferent nerves (Egerod et al., 2018), making 
the vagus susceptible to microbial-produced metabolites and neuro­
transmitters. In line with this, administration of the short-chain fatty 
acid, butyrate, affected vagus nerve activity in anesthetized rats (Lal 
et al., 2001). Certain gut bacteria, such as Escherichia coli and Bifido­
bacterium longum, activate vagus afferent neurons (Bercik et al., 2011; 
Gakis et al., 2009; Goehler et al., 2005) through neuropods (Kaelberer 
et al., 2020). Neuropods synapse with the vagus nodose to transduce 
signals from the gut to the brain in milliseconds using glutamate as a 
neurotransmitter (Kaelberer et al., 2020). In animal models, increased 
vagus activation was shown to occur with probiotic supplementation 
(Lactobacillus johnsonii La1 (Tanida et al., 2005) and Bifidobacterium 
Infantis (Sudo et al., 2004)). Interestingly, vagotomy prevented the 
restorative effect of probiotics on anxiety (Bifidobacterium longum 
NCC3001 (Bercik et al., 2011); Lactobacillus rhamnosus JB-1 (Bravo et al., 
2011)). Also, the effects of Lactobacillus gasseri NK109 are attenuated 
with celiac vagotomy (Yun et al., 2020). Furthermore, the vagus nerve is 
activated by infections or immune challenges with bacterial lipopoly­
saccharide, and sickness and anxiety behavior can be attenuated when 
the vagus nerve is cut (Bercik et al., 2011; Goehler et al., 2005; Kittana 
et al., 2018; Lyte et al., 2006). 
7. Therapeutic importance of the vagus nerve 
It is noteworthy that recovery from depression can be facilitated by 
stimulating the vagus nerve. This can be achieved through direct elec­
trical vagus nerve stimulation (VNS), peripheral vagus nerve stimulation 
(tVNS), slow-paced deep breathing and altering the gut microbiome 
through dietary and lifestyle changes (Austelle et al., 2022; Tatschl and 
Schwerdtfeger, 2022). Currently, vagus nerve stimulation is a treatment 
option for treatment-resistant depression, as outlined in international 
psychiatric guidelines (Schlaepfer et al., 2004), however, it is an inva­
sive procedure requiring surgery and not widely available. Psycho­
biotics are subtypes of probiotics that modify the gut-brain axis and lead 
to alterations in mood, anxiety and cognitive function (Dinan et al., 
2013). 
Nowadays, 
the 
term 
psychobiotics 
includes 
all 
microbiota-targeted interventions, such as probiotics and prebiotics, 
that influence the gut-brain axis to improve mental health (Sarkar et al., 
2016). Importantly, future studies should investigate how modulating 
the gut microbiome through psychobiotics, such as dietary interventions 
and probiotics, could affect vagus nerve functioning in health and dis­
ease (Bonaz et al., 2018; Carreno and Frazer, 2017; Wu et al., 2018) and 
how peripherical stimulation of the vagus nerve (e.g., electrically or via 
slow-paced deep breathing (Tatschl and Schwerdtfeger, 2022) could 
modify the gut microbiome. 
8. Conclusion and outlook 
For many years and maybe unconsciously, psychiatrists have treated 
the gut microbiome and the gut brain axis, including the vagus nerve, 
using psychotropic medications resulting in changes in microbiome 
composition and function (Cussotto et al., 2019). In the future, inter­
ventional studies should be done with combinations of conventional 
psychotropics, probiotics and nutraceuticals targeting vagus nerve 
function to create a favourable internal environment. Also, HRV mea­
surements could be used as an easily accessible, routine marker to 
identify patients who could benefit from adjunctive targeted psycho­
biotic interventions, in addition to conventional antidepressant treat­
ment. Holistic thinking in psychiatry is essential to keep the body in 
mind by improving both its vagus connection to the brain, the gut 
microbiome and to the outside world through social interactions and 
contact with diverse microbes. 
Author statement 
The authors confirm that the submitted review article is original 
work and it has not been published elsewhere, nor is it being considered 
for publication in another journal. This narrative review is based on a 
lecture given by author SM at the International Psychoneur­
oendocrinology Experts Meeting in Günzburg, Germany, March-April 
2023. 
